19 ELIMINATE TURNPIKE AUTHORITY REPORTING REQUIREMENTS
20 SECTION 5. G.S. 136-89.193 reads as rewritten:
21 "§ 136-89.193. Annual plan of work; annual and quarterly reports.report.
22 (a) Annual Plan of Work. – The Authority shall annually develop a plan of work for the
23 fiscal year, describing the activities and projects to be undertaken, accompanied by a budget.
24 This annual plan of work shall be subject to the concurrence of the Board of Transportation.
25 (b) Annual Reports. Report. – The Authority shall, promptly following the close of each
26 fiscal year, submit an annual report of its activities for the preceding fiscal year and an annual
27 audit of its books and accounts for the preceding fiscal year to the Governor, the General
28 Assembly, and the Department of Transportation. The report and audit shall be submitted no later
29 than October 31 of the fiscal year in which the report and audit are completed.
30 The North Carolina Turnpike Authority shall report to the Joint Legislative Transportation
31 Oversight Committee on January 31, 2017, and in its annual report thereafter, the number of
32 one-time toll facility users who are charged more than fifty dollars ($50.00) in processing fees
33 imposed under G.S. 136-89.215 and civil penalties assessed under G.S. 136-89.216.
34 (c) Repealed by Session Laws 2016-90, s. 4, effective July 11, 2016.
35 (d) Report Prior to Let of Contracts. – The Authority shall consult with and report to the
36 Joint Legislative Transportation Oversight Committee and the Joint Legislative Commission on
37 Governmental Operations prior to the letting of any contract for Turnpike Project construction
38 authorized under G.S. 136-183(a)(2).
39 (e) Repealed by Session Laws 2011-145, s. 28.35(a), effective July 1, 2011."
40
41 TURNPIKE UNPAID TOLL NOTICE BY ELECTRONIC MAIL
42 SECTION 6. G.S. 136-89.214(a) reads as rewritten:
43 "(a) Bill. – If a motor vehicle travels on a Turnpike project that uses an open road tolling
44 system and a toll for traveling on the project is not paid prior to travel or at the time of travel, the
45 Authority must send a bill by first-class mail to the registered owner of the motor vehicle or the
46 person who had care, custody, and control of the vehicle as established under G.S. 136-89.212(b)
47 for the amount of the unpaid toll; provided, however, that with the written consent of the
48 registered owner of the motor vehicle or the person who had care, custody, and control of the
49 vehicle as set forth above, the Authority may send the bill via electronic mail to a designated
50 electronic mail account or electronic mail account on file with a state Department of Motor
51 Vehicles rather than by first-class mail. The Authority must send the bill within 90 days after the
DRS15166-MW-58 Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 travel occurs, or within 90 days of receipt of a sworn affidavit submitted under
2 G.S. 136-89.212(b) identifying the person who had care, custody, and control of the motor
3 vehicle. If a bill is not sent within the required time, the Authority waives collection of the toll.
4 The Authority must establish a billing period for unpaid open road tolls that is no shorter than 15
5 days. A bill for a billing period must include all unpaid tolls incurred by the same person during
6 the billing period."
7
8 REMOVE LIMIT ON TURNPIKE PROJECTS
9 SECTION 7. G.S. 136-89.183(a)(2) reads as rewritten:
10 "(2) To study, plan, develop, and undertake preliminary design work on Turnpike
11 Projects. At the conclusion of these activities, the Turnpike Authority is
12 authorized to design, establish, purchase, construct, operate, and maintain no
13 more than eleven projects, which shall include include, but not be limited to,
14 the following:
15 a. Triangle Expressway, including segments also known as N.C. 540,
16 Triangle Parkway, Phases 1 and 2 of Complete 540, and the Western
17 Wake Freeway in Wake and Durham Counties. The described
18 segments constitute one project.
19 b. Repealed by Session Laws 2013-183, s. 5.1, effective July 1, 2013.
20 c. Monroe Connector/Bypass.
21 d., e. Repealed by Session Laws 2013-183, s. 5.1, effective July 1, 2013.
22 f. Repealed by Session Laws 2008-225, s. 4, effective August 17, 2008.
23 Any other project proposed by the Authority in addition to the projects listed
24 in this subdivision requires prior consultation with the Joint Legislative
25 Commission on Governmental Operations pursuant to G.S. 120-76.1 no less
26 than 180 days prior to initiating the process required by Article 7 of Chapter
27 159 of the General Statutes.
28 With the exception of the two projects set forth in sub subdivisions a. and c.
29 of this subdivision, the Turnpike projects selected for construction by the
30 Turnpike Authority, prior to the letting of a contract for the project, shall meet
31 the following conditions: (i) two of the projects must be ranked in the top 35
32 based on total score on the Department produced list entitled "Mobility Fund
33 Project Scores" dated June 6, 2012, and, in addition, may be subject to
34 G.S. 136-18(39a); (ii) of the projects not ranked as provided in (i), one may
35 be subject to G.S. 136-18(39a); (iii) the projects shall be included in any
36 applicable locally adopted comprehensive transportation plans; (iv) the
37 projects shall be shown in the current State Transportation Improvement
38 Program; and (v) toll projects must be approved by all affected Metropolitan
39 Planning Organizations and Rural Transportation Planning Organizations for
40 tolling."
41
42 CLARIFY USE OF REVENUE FROM TURNPIKE PROJECTS
43 SECTION 8. G.S. 136-89.188(a) reads as rewritten:
44 "(a) Revenues derived from a Turnpike Project authorized under this Article shall be used
45 only for the following costs associated with the Project from which the revenue was derived or a
46 planned contiguous toll facility:facility identified in a transportation plan adopted by an affected
47 Metropolitan Planning Organization:
48 (1) Authority administration costs.
49 (2) Development, right-of-way acquisition, design, construction, expansion,
50 operation, maintenance, reconstruction, rehabilitation, and replacement costs.
