29 EXEMPT FERRY DIVISION FROM TEMPORARY SOLUTIONS PROGRAM
30 SECTION 10. G.S. 126-6.3(a) reads as rewritten:
31 "(a) Use of Temporary Solutions Required for Cabinet Agencies. – Notwithstanding
32 G.S. 126-5 or any other provision of law, all Cabinet agencies that utilize temporary employees
33 to perform work that is not information technology-related shall employ them through the
34 Temporary Solutions Program administered by the Office of State Human Resources (OSHR).
35 Council of State agencies may use the Temporary Solutions Program in the discretion of the
36 agency. The Department of Transportation, Ferry Division, is exempt from the required use of
37 the Temporary Solutions Program when there is an established need for peak season hires or
38 when the work requires a specific skill set beyond the scope of temporary employees."
39
40 MODIFY STIP REPORTING AND LOCAL CONSULTATION REQUIREMENTS
41 SECTION 11. G.S. 136-12 reads as rewritten:
42 "§ 136-12. Reports to General Assembly; Transportation Improvement Program posted
43 and submitted to members and staff of General Assembly.
44 (a) The Department of Transportation shall shall, on or before the tenth day after the
45 convening of each regular session of the General Assembly, make a full printed and detailed
46 report to the Joint Legislative Transportation Oversight Committee by March 1 of each year on
47 how the previous fiscal year's funds for the General Assembly that includes the cost of
48 maintenance and construction were allocated and expended. The work undertaken by the
49 Department, receipts of license fees, disbursements of the Department, and other financial
50 information relevant to illustrate the Department's financial condition during the previous fiscal
51 year. For maintenance and construction work undertaken by the Department, the report shall also
DRS15166-MW-58 Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 include expenditures of both State and federal funds and shall be in sufficient detail that the
2 county can be identified. A full account of each road project shall be kept by and under the
3 direction of the Department of Transportation or its representatives, to ascertain at any time the
4 expenditures and the liabilities against all projects; also records of contracts and force account
5 work. The account records, together with all supporting documents, shall be open at all times to
6 the inspection of the Governor or road authorities of any county, or their authorized
7 representatives, and copies thereof shall be furnished such officials upon request.
8 …."
