10 AUTHORIZE ELECTRONIC PAYMENT TRANSACTION FEE FOR FERRIES
11 SECTION 12. G.S. 136-82 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
12 "(b3) Transaction Fee Authorized for Electronic Payment. – When the Department of
13 Transportation accepts electronic payment, as that term is defined in G.S. 147-86.20, for any toll
14 or fee authorized under this Article, the Department may add a transaction fee to each electronic
15 payment transaction to offset the service charge the Department pays for electronic payment
16 service. The transaction fee authorized under this subsection shall not exceed two percent (2%)
17 of the electronic payment."
18
19 MODIFICATIONS TO PROPERTY RIGHTS IN THE ACQUISITION AND
20 CONDEMNATION OF PROPERTY BY THE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION
21 SECTION 13.(a) G.S. 136-108 reads as rewritten:
22 "§ 136-108. Determination of issues other than damages.
23 (a) After the filing of the plat, the judge, upon motion and 10 days' notice by either the
24 Department of Transportation or the owner, shall, either in or out of term, hear and determine
25 any and all issues raised by the pleadings other than the issue of damages, including, but not
26 limited to, if controverted, questions of necessary and proper parties, title to the land, interest
27 taken, and area taken.
28 (b) The effect of the imposition of easements, including, but not limited to, permanent
29 utility easements, aerial utility easements, permanent drainage easements, permanent drainage
30 utility easements, temporary construction easements, temporary drainage easements, temporary
31 utility easements, and slope easements, is an issue of damages and shall not be subject to
32 consideration pursuant to this section."
33 SECTION 13.(b) G.S. 136-112 reads as rewritten:
34 "§ 136-112. Measure of damages.
35 The following shall be the measure of damages to be followed by the commissioners, jury or
36 judge who determines the issue of damages:
37 (1) Where only a part of a tract is taken, the measure of damages for said taking
38 shall be the difference between the fair market value of the entire tract
39 immediately prior to said taking and the fair market value of the remainder
40 immediately after said taking, with consideration being given to any special
41 or general benefits resulting from the utilization of the part taken for highway
42 purposes.
43 (2) Where the entire tract is taken the measure of damages for said taking shall be
44 the fair market value of the property at the time of taking.
45 (3) Evidence of the damages resulting from the imposition of easements,
46 including, but not limited to, permanent utility easements, aerial utility
47 easements, permanent drainage easements, permanent drainage utility
48 easements, temporary construction easements, temporary drainage easements,
49 temporary utility easements, and slope easements, shall not be presumed to be
50 based on the Department of Transportation exercising its rights to the fullest
Page 6 DRS15166-MW-58

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 extent of the law but shall be based on consideration of the project plans and
2 other admissible market evidence."
3 SECTION 13.(c) G.S. 136-89.52 reads as rewritten:
4 "§ 136-89.52. Acquisition of property and property rights.
5 (a) For the purposes of this Article, the Department of Transportation may acquire private
6 or public property and property rights for controlled-access facilities and service or frontage
7 roads, including rights of access, air, view and light, by gift, devise, purchase, or condemnation
8 in the same manner as now or hereafter authorized by law to acquire such property or property
9 rights in connection with highways. The property rights acquired under the provisions of this
10 Article may be in fee simple or an appropriate easement for right-of-way in perpetuity. In
11 connection with the acquisition of property or property rights for any controlled-access facility
12 or portion thereof, or frontage road in connection therewith, the Department of Transportation
13 may, in its discretion, with the consent of the landowner, acquire an entire lot, parcel, or tract of
14 land, if by so doing, the interests of the public will be best served, even though said entire lot,
15 parcel, or tract is not immediately needed for the right-of-way proper.
16 (b) Along new controlled-access highway locations, abutting property owners shall not
17 be entitled to access to such new locations, and no abutter's easement of access to such new
18 locations shall attach to said property. Where part of a tract of land is taken or acquired for the
19 construction of a controlled-access facility on a new location, the nature of the facility
20 constructed on the part taken, including the fact that there shall be no direct access thereto, shall
21 be considered in determining the fair market value of the remaining property immediately after
22 the taking.
23 (c) In no event shall the imposition of easements, including permanent utility easements,
24 aerial utility easements, permanent drainage easements, permanent drainage utility easements,
25 temporary construction easements, temporary drainage easements, temporary utility easements,
26 and slope easements, be construed to constitute the imposition of new control-of-access or the
27 taking of the property owner's abutters easement of access."
28 SECTION 13.(d) This section becomes effective July 31, 2025, and applies to causes
29 of action arising on or after that date.
30
31 EFFECTIVE DATE
32 SECTION 14. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
33 law.
